put: 12\nExplanation: The best possible way to form 3 subarrays is: [10,3], [1], and [1] at a total cost of 10 + 1 + 1 = 12.\nIt can be shown that 12 is the minimum cost achievable.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n3 <= n <= 50\n1 <= nums[i] <= 50\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumCost(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumCost(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        # The first element is always part of the cost\n        first_element_cost = nums[0]\n        \n        # We need to find the two smallest elements after the first element\n        # because these will be the starting elements of the second and third subarrays\n        # to minimize the cost.\n        remaining_elements = nums[1:]\n        remaining_elements.sort()\n        \n        # The minimum cost will be the first element plus the two smallest elements from the rest\n        return first_element_cost + remaining_elements[0] + remaining_elements[1]\n```\n\nThis solution works as follows:\n1. The cost of the first subarray is always the first element of the array.\n2. To minimize the total cost, we need to choose the smallest possible starting elements for the second and third subarrays.\n3. Therefore, we sort the remaining elements of the array and pick the two smallest ones.\n4. The result is the sum of the first element and these two smallest elements.", "estimated_date": 1705190400000}